The Real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China it is the Long March - a story comparable to the Exodus of the Israelites from Egypt led by Moses.
I grew up with it.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their southern strongholds by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and impassable grasslands, with Mao leading the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope against incredible odds, the Red Armies reached northwestern China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, badly battered, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
To what extent does China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the beginning of the Long March, I set out in search of its traces.
It is still a terrifying journey through regions that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I located 40 of them and had conversations with them – they were ordinary people who had been left behind or had made it to the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, barely taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and was not released until Huang agreed.
He thought about fleeing, but stayed, out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many ran away.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the army's first major engagement on the march.
Yet at most 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, at the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. It is said that 22 brave men overpowered a regiment of nationalist troops that was guarding the chains of the Luding Bridge with machine guns, and cleared the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu was the most significant event of the entire Long March, and so it is still praised today as such.
Yet documents that I have seen suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu first told the Party historians a completely different story. "The matter was not as complicated as people later presented it," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should respect the truth.
How they present it is another matter."
So the legend continues.
There was only a bit of bickering above the Dadu.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial post in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were heading.
There were constant discussions about the ultimate goal.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
Yet the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
Women were ordered to turn around and go back home because there was not enough food.
Less than a month after the unification of the three Red Armies, the Party decided that the Long March had to continue.
But she was saved by the kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek by the general that Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
Not however for the 21,000 men and women of the West Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and had the mission to cross the western Chinese border to seek help from Russia.
But Mao sent them contradictory orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Enclosed on barren land, where survival was difficult, they were wiped out by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or taken prisoner.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Nevertheless, it is missing from official historical accounts.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
That was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the Party and to deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, despaired, and endured.
Hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages in order to extort ransom.
The liquidations continued until practically no officers were left to take command in the battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They bore their martyrdom with a courage and self-sacrifice that is unmatched in the history of China and other peoples.

What drove her to do so?
I questioned one of the top generals about what he knew about communism back then. "I had no idea then, just as I do now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself really knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope for a just and progressive society.
Perhaps no one knew – or could know – how much suffering was yet to come, how great the sacrifice and how enormous the difference between dream and reality would be.
